Deploying a Static Website on Azure Using PowerShell 
Today I automated the full workflow of deploying a static website on Azure using only Azure PowerShell 

1. Create a Storage Account
Static websites require a StorageV2 account with public blob access enabled.
New-AzStorageAccount `
    -Name "az104storage02" `
    -ResourceGroupName "azure-104-rg" `
    -Location "EastUS" `
    -SkuName "Standard_LRS" `
    -AllowBlobPublicAccess $true `
    -Kind StorageV2

2. Fetch Storage Account Context
This context object is needed for all further operations.
$storageAccount = Get-AzStorageAccount `
    -ResourceGroupName "azure-104-rg" `
    -Name "az104sanjeevdemostorage"
$ctx = $storageAccount.Context

3. Enable Static Website Hosting
Azure will auto-create a special container named $web.
Enable-AzStorageStaticWebsite `
    -Context $ctx `
    -IndexDocument "index.html" `
    -ErrorDocument404Path "error.html"

4. Upload the Website Files
Upload index.html into the $web container.
Set-AzStorageBlobContent `
    -File "C:\Users\User\Desktop\index.html" `
    -Container "`$web" `
    -Context $ctx

5. Get the Website URL
This gives you your public static website endpoint.
$storageAccount = Get-AzStorageAccount `
    -ResourceGroupName "azure-104-rg" `
    -Name "az104sanjeevdemostorage"
$storageAccount.PrimaryEndpoints.Web

Takeaway
✔ Storage Account created
 ✔ Static Website hosting enabled
 ✔ index.html uploaded
 ✔ Public endpoint retrieved
Your site is now live on Azure, just like AWS S3 static hosting — but fully automated using PowerShell.